{
  "card_id": "relevant_high_relevant_low",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Relevant High / Relevant Low",
  "aliases": [
    "Relevant Highs and Lows",
    "relevant swing high/low",
    "Relevant Swings",
    "significant price level"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A price level with market structure significance, typically a prior day/week high/low or swing extreme with sufficient separation from adjacent swings, where price reversals or reactions are expected to form.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify prior day or week highs and lows as relevant levels.",
    "Identify swing highs and swing lows on the chart with valid separation (sufficient price distance) from adjacent same-direction swings.",
    "Avoid arbitrary highs/lows; ensure the level has structural significance.",
    "When price breaks a relevant high/low and forms an 'expansion met with expansion' structure, that level is a valid reversal point.",
    "A relevant high/low should explain subsequent price reversal behavior without leaving ignored failed swings.",
    "Failed swings (clustered highs/lows) do not constitute relevant swings; ignore them and look for extreme points.",
    "Use a lookback period of three higher-timeframe candles (including current) to determine relevance; swings beyond this range are no longer relevant.",
    "When price enters a relevant swing point, observe whether a reversal, retracement, or breakout forms to judge its validity.",
    "A relevant swing point should produce a clear price reaction, not be easily breached."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Relevant highs/lows are key reference levels for expected reversals. Traders should watch for reversal structures (e.g., expansion met with expansion) on lower timeframes when price touches these levels. Entry can be based on fractal models (e.g., candle 2 or 3 close). Stop placement should avoid failed swings. Targets are derived from these levels. If price reverses at a non-relevant level, the reversal may fail.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Selecting arbitrary highs/lows for reversal trades, leading to price breaking through instead of reversing.",
    "Ignoring obvious relevant levels like prior day/week highs/lows and trading unclear structures.",
    "Anticipating reversals before price reaches a relevant high/low, causing failed trades.",
    "Failing to check if a relevant high/low leaves a failed swing; if so, the level is not relevant enough.",
    "Mistaking failed swings (clustered highs/lows) for relevant swings, leading to positions at untrustworthy levels.",
    "Neglecting valid separation; attempting reversals when adjacent swings are too close.",
    "Considering old swings beyond the three-candle lookback period as relevant, leading to poor target selection.",
    "Entering prematurely before price action confirms a reaction at the relevant level (e.g., waiting for candle close).",
    "Confusing relevant swings with failed swings, failing to identify truly tradable levels."
  ],
